{"/service/ndnp/vi/batch_vi_cartier_ver01/data/sn94060041/00542866779/1930030801/0160.xml":{"full_text":"HALLWOOD\nMr. Roy D. Bull Jias accepted a\nposition in Pocomoke.\nMr. Nat Taylor and family spent\nSunday in Cape Charles.\nlittle Miss Doris Collins is oh\nthe sick list. We wish her a speedy\nrecovery.\nMiss Helen Sturgis visited her\nparents at Pungoteague for the\nweek-end.\nMr\u00ae. C. B. Sterling and daughter,\nLois, motored to Pocomoke, Sunday i\nafternoon.\nMr. Bunk Collins, of New Jersey,1,\nis spending a few days with his 1\nfamily here.\nMi's. Arinthia Hurley, who has;\nbeen visiting her son at Saxis, has;\nreturned home.\n'Mr. knd Mrs. A1 Ward, of Cris-j\nfield, were the guests of Mrs. W.\nH. Hitchens, Sunday.\nWe are glad to see Mr. Fred\nHall out agpin, after being indis\nposed for some time.\nMiss Vivian Hurley spent Wed\nnesday nijjht with Miss Gladys Mar\nshall, of Temperanceville.\nMiss Lois Sterling and Mrs. Roxie\nLewi\u00ae spent Friday night with Mrs.\nRoy Phillips, of Onancock. v\nMrs. Edward Russell and family\nspent Sunday with her parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. Frank Lankford.\nMisses JoLsephine Metcalf, of\nMappeville, and Hattie Reva Parks\nspent Monday with Miss Hattie\nBull.\nMrs. A. P. Bull and Mr. Richard\nHitchens arrived home Sunday morn\ning, after spending a few days in\nBaltimore.\nMr. J. T. Lewis arrived home\n\u2019inday, after spending a few day's\nwith his son, Mr. Milton Lewis, of\nWilmington, Del.\nMrs. Arthur Northam and daugh\nter, Anna, from Pocomoke, were\nguests in the home of Mrs. W. H.\nHitchens last week.\nMr And Mrs. Franklin Britting\nham and son, Vaughn, spent Sunday\nwith her parents, Mr. and Mrs. J.\nA. Taylor, of Withams.\nSAXIS\nMr. Harley Mister recently pur\nchased a Ford touring car.\nMr. Hugh Glenn has recently pur\nchased a new Chevrolet coach.\nOapt. Marvin Drewer returned Sat\nurday with a load of seed oysters.\nMt. \u201cNuke\u201d Lewis and family, oi\nPocomoke City,, spent Sunday witt\nrelatives of Saxis.\nWe have been informed that Mr\nWill Glenn contemplates the pur\nchase of the house and lot of Johr\nW. Marshall.\nMr. Newman Lanton, 01\nton, was with relatives of this\nplace Saturday night and Sunday.\nAfter spending Saturday evening\nand Sunday morning with relatives,\nMr. Carson Martin, of Wilmington,\nreturned to resume work, Monday.\nMr. W. C. Lewis, who had a slight\nstroke of paralysis 4 some time ago,\nis very feeble.\nMessrs. Walter and John Drewer.:\nJr. and their wives ,of Craddock-j\nville, were with their parents, Mr. I\nand Mrs. L. M. Drewer Saturday j\nand Sunday.\nCapt. Norman Hurley arrived Sat\nurday evening with a load of about\nfifteen hundred bushels of seed oys\nters from North Carolina for Mr.\nHerman Onley.\nAs it was so stormy Monday only\na few of the boatmen working on\nthe seaside who spent Saturday and\nSunday with their families, returned\nbefore Tuesday.\nCapts. Marvin Drewer, Garland\nWeaver and Claude Drewer will I\noverhaul and fix up for buying\nand running fish from the Western\nShore of Chesapeake and its tribu\ntaries to Crisfield, Md. in a few\ndays.\nMr. Roy Linton left last week\nfor North Carolina after a load of\nseed oysters for his father, Mr.\nSewell J. Linton of D. v\nThe little daughter of Mr. T. W.\nByrd, who has been sick for sev\nJ eral days, we are glad to know, is\nout again.\nj Mr. Willie Linton left Tuesday toj\naccompany Capt. Howard Drewer,\nof Crisfield, to North Carolina toj\npurchase seed oysters for a Mr.j\nWebb, of the Eastern Shore of\nMaryland, to be planted in Chinco-j\nteague Bay.\nMr. Joseph Rhodes has been catch\ning a few- shad and herring the\npast week. The trappers antid\npate a good fish season.\nCapt. Cornelius Drewer arrived j\nTuesday with a load of about two;\nthousand bushels of seed oysters j\nfrom North Carolina for Mr. H. A.\nDrewer and son, Vernon.\nCurlee Clothes for Men\naffmoderate prices.\nA. Greenberg Co.,\nOnancock, Va.\nSANFORD\nMr. Spencer Godwin is on the sick\nlist. t\u2018\nMr. J. W. Onley is still ill at this\nwriting.\nMr. W. W. Fisher has purchased\na Ford truck.\nMr. L. T. Fisher has purchased a\nChevrolet truck.\nMrs. W. J. Fisher shopped in\nSalisbury, Saturday.\nDr. O. It.. Fletcher has purchased\na new Chevrolet, coupe.\nMrs. lsittie Boston, of. Marion,\nMt}.,,\u2019? visiting Mrs. A. W. Swift.\nMiss Laura Byrd, who has been in\ndisposed with the mumps is now\nbetter.\nMiss Thelma Drewer, of Saxis,\nspent. Tuesday night with Miss Jua\nnita DrummoiuJ.\nMr. and Mrs. Lenora Stant and\nMr. J. E. Middleton motored to\nCape Charles, Sunday.\nMr. Washington Hall who has been\nconfined to his bed for some rime is\nstill, sick at this writing.\nMrs. Penn Corbin, of Pocomoke\nCity, Md., spent the week-end with\nher father, Mr. G. F. Byrd.\nMrs. M. Z. Stant, who has been\non the sick list for some time, we\nare glad to say is improving.\nMrs. Milford Smith, of Messongo,\nspent Wednesday night with her\ngrandmother, Mrs. Amanda Stant.\nMr. Winfred Witham, of Phila\ndelphia, spent Sunday with his par\nents, Mr. and Mrs. M. E. Witham1.\nThose Who are. confined to their\nI homes, with the mumps are Mrs. M.\nA. Drummond ami 'son, Lynwood,\nMiss Florence Hall and Miss Juanita\nDrummond.\nWe were- very sorry to hear of the\n\nsudden death of our neighbor, Mr.\nA. W. Swift. The community ex-1\ntends sympathy to his wife and son j\nin their bereavement.\nMr. G. P. Byrd and children,\nFrank and Laura, and Mr. and Mrs.\nW. K. Byrd and family were the\nguestf) of Mr. and Mrs. Roy Byrd,\nof Hopeton, at a six o\u2019clock dinner!\nSunday.\nRev. F. F. Fulcher and family,\ncalled on Mrs. Meady Drummond,\nWednesday night. The music which\nwas rendered by them was enjoyed\nby all. Those present were Misses\nAlma Fletcher, Thelma Drewer,\nHelen Marshall, Mrs. Arintha Corbin\nGreene, Mrs. Dollie Bundick, Mr.\nLeslie Drummond, Misses Juanita j\nDrummond, Alice Fisher, Kathleen j\nand Ivan Godwin.\nHOPETON\nMrs. W. F. Thornton is slowly im-'\nproving, after a long illness.\nWe are glad to report that Mrs.j\nS. E. Hickman is out again, after!\nbeing badly burned.\nMr. and Mrs. Herbert Colona, of\nAcconiac, spent the week-end with\nher parents, Mr. and Mrs. E. B.\nGrey.\nRev. J. P. Essex was the guest\nof Mr. and Mrs. C. W. Colona\nSaturday evening at a four o\u2019clock\ndinner. j\nMr. and Mrs. J. T. Justis, of\nPiarksley, Mr. Harry Wessells, Mr.\nand Mrs. A. L. Gladtding were the\nguests of Mr. and Mrs. James Glad-.\nding, Sunday.\nMisses Helen Shrieves, Mattie\nMiller and Messrs. Norman Evans\nj and Lewis Shrieves, of Onancock,\nspent Sunday afternoon with Miss\nThelma Gladding.\nSubscribe to the Peninsula Enter\ni prise, Ijl.C.O a year'in advance.\nThere\u2019s a blend of I.G.A. Tea to satisfy your Tea\nTaste, at a price you\u2019ll want to pay. Visit your\nnearest I.G.A. Store today\u2014learn\nmore about tnis new i.u.a. f amily\n\u00bband the many other food values\nthat help you beat your budget.\n\n1GB friendship Offer\nGet this beautiful Green Glass Set A\nat your I. G. A. Store for only 31c I y\nwith purchase of 1 pound I. G. A. W*\nCoffee, or 1 package I. G. A. Tea,\nand any other 1. G. A. Brand item.\nI. G. A. OKAJNGJi\nPEKOE TEA\ni lb 91 p\nItjr.Aal-LL\nApricots\nMATCHES\n6 Boxes ior.\nSPINACH\nNo. 2>/z Can....\nMALT\nBlue Ribbon.\n19c\n15c\n57c\nCampbell\u2019s\nPuffed Wheat\nMacaroni\nI. li. A. OKAJNUE\nPEKOE TEA\n1 \\z 07:\nPkR.\nf. G. A. Brand\nNo, 2 y2 Can.\nLUX\nPer pkft.\nJELLY\nShimmoH's, 2 for.\nSALT\nMorton's., 2 pkgs..\n9c\n27c\n10c\n25c\n15c\nTomato Soup OQ/\u00bb\n3 Cans for.\u00abOv\nPkg.\n12c\nSpaghetti Noodles QP\u201e\n3 Pkg.&OKs\nMEARS\nMr. Milton Byrd made a business\ntrip to Salisbury, Monday.\nMr. Willard Pilchard, of Poco\nmoke City, was a caller in town\nSunday.\nMr. William Davis is now working\nfor Mr. Waldon Tiaylw, of Temper\naneeville.\nMr. John W. Nontham, of Hall\nwood, visited Mr. and Mrs. Fred\nGladding, Tuesday. v\nMessrs. Otho Taylor and Walter\nEwell, of Bloxom, motored to New\nYork City, Saturday.\nMrs. Marvin Bull, of Hailwood,\nspent Tuesday with her parents, Mr.\nand Mrs. Lee F. Davis.\nMr. and Mrs. Claude Hughes and'\nsons, Elwood and Willard, shopped\nin Pocomoke City, Saturday night.\nMr. .and Mrs. E. R. Bloxom spent\nSunday in \\he home of Mr. and j\nMrs. B. J. Whealton at Oak Hall, j\nMr. and Mrs. Ernest Taylor, of|\nMessongo, spent Sunday with Mr.\nTaylor\u2019s mother, Mrs. Louise Tay-j\nlor.\nMiss' Catholene Trader, of Green\nbackville, spent the week-end with\nher parents, Mr. and Mrs. A. T.\nTrader.\nMr. and Mrs. Wesley Dryden, of\nPocomoke City, Md., spent Sunday\nin the home of Mr. and Mrs. Jake\nMarshall.\nMr. Winston Brown, of the Uni\nversity of Richmond, spfent the week\nend with his parents, Mr. and Mrs.\nC, H. Brown.\nMr. Melvin Bloxom and mother,\nMrs. George Bloxom, motored to j\nSalisbury, Monday. They were ac\ncompanied by Mrs. Paul Chesser,\nof Sign Post.\nNELSONIA\nMr. and Mrs. W. L. Ayres have\nmoved into the house of Mrs. Kitty\nBull.\nThe G. A. T.. Sewing Circle met\nwith Mrs. C. L. Meairs, Tuesday\nevening.\nMr. and Mrs. C. L. Mears spent\nSunday gfternoon with Mr. arid Mrs.\nLloyd, McCready, of Onley.\nMrs. Edward BuncUck spent Sun\nday afternoon with Mr. and Mrs.\nR. K. Savage, of Mappsville.\nThose on the sick list are Mrs.\nJohn Middleton, Mrs. Major Dix,\nMrs. Milford Hickman and Miss\nMannie Young.\nMr. and Mrs. William Pettit and\nson, Grafton, of Parksley, spent Sun-\nday afternoon with Mr. and Mrs.\nGordon Gravenor.\nWe are glad to report that lit\ntle Alva Grace Kilmon, who has j\nbeen ill with pneumonia, is able to\nbe out again. I\nMr. and Mrs. R. W. Trader and)\ndaughter, Marcella, of Melfa, spent j\nSaturday evening with Mr. and Mrs.1.\nDonald Kilmon.\nRUE\nOur farmers are quite busy plant\ning white potatoes and getting hot\nbeds ready for'seed sweet potatoes.\nMr. and Mrs. Edward Baker put\nchased a Willys Six Coach from\nBloxom Auto Co., of Mappsvillle last\nweek.\nMr. and Mrs. William Bloxom, of\nMappsville. have been recent gucsti*\nof Mrs. Bloxom\u2019s parents, Mr. and\nMrs. O. J. Littleton.\nMr. and Mrs. Edward Baker, Mrs.\nM. W. Krazirisky, Mrs. Cecil Baker.\nMrs. W. A. Baker and Mrs. Henry\nAdams attended the funeral of Mrs.\nWalter Smith at the Chincoteague\nBaptist Church, Sunday, March 2nd.\nMrs. Smith died at the hoipe of her\nson in Chester, Pa., February 28.\nSTOCKHOLDERS MEETIN?r\nThe annual meeting of the stock\nholders of the Wachapreague Bank\ning Co., will be held at the banking\nhouse at Wachapreague, Va., Friday,\nApril 4th, at 2 p. m. to elect direc\ntors for the ensuing years and the\ntransaction of any other business,\nthat may come before the meeting.\nO. Fuller Hall, Cashier.\nSee our snappy line of\nhigh grade Spring Coats\nat $10.95 and $15.95.\nA. Greenberg Co.,\nOnancock, Va.\nCooperation Means Progress\u2014Progress Brings Success\nSweet Potato Fertilizers\nt 4<v \u2018.V'\nt*V c ,V 'M-..-'-\nThe use of high grade fertilizers is one of the\nmost valuable but also the most expensive adjunct to\ntruck growing.\nThe quality of fertilizers us\u00a3d,t their high cost,\n-running into, millions annually on the Eastern Shore,\nand their vaiue in producing fine class products make\nthe fertilizer question worthy of careful thought. We\nappreciate the fact that trucking \u201ccannot be done\nwithout the use of good fertilizers and would empha\nsize that they should be selected to fit the needs of\nthe crop, and so applied that, they will be utilized to\n4he best advantage.\nv.\"' The value of certain formulas is quite definitely\ndetermined for .white potato production. The 7-6-5\nformula has no superior on most of our soils. The\nratio and sources of nitrogenous ingredients have been\nstudied and put into general use. However, we find\nas time goes on that many of the time honored\nsources of nitrogen, such as, cotton seed meal and\nother w'ell known organics, are becoming scarcer,\nand there is a growing tendency to use a larger per\ncentage of natural inorganics, or synthetics, on ac\ncount of their lower cost. The use of synthetic\nfertilizers for white potatoes as well as other crops,\nand the way to use them will have to have future\nattention on account of the cost factor that is in\nvolved.\nSpecial formulas for sweet potatoes are not so\nwell established. We believe the best formula is not\nyet in general use. The development of oversize\u2019\nstock indicates an over abundance of nitrogen late in\nthe season; the poor keeping quality may be the\nresult of poorly balanced, food supply. There is\nevery reason to feel, that a change in sweet potato\nfertilizer formulas might be desirable. It now ap\npears that reliable information from our own section,\nat our own Experiment Station, warrants the use of\nspecial formulas. We will discuss this matter briefly\nat this time so that it may be considered before the\nfarmers make their purchases for the year.\nSweet Potato Fertilizer Formulas Recommended:\nThe Norfolk Truck Experiment Station after nine\nyears careful investigation of fertilizer formulas for\nsweet potatoes under Eastern Shore conditions un\nhesitatingly recommend the use of a 4-4-20 formula,\nthat is, 4% ammonia, 4% phosphate and 20% potash.\nThis formula has superseded the 3-3-15 which was\nfirst used in the experiments, since the ingredients\nused in its preparation are more desirable and are\ncheaper in proportion to the amount of plant food\nthat they carry. Furthermore, only 75% as many\npounds of this formula need be used as that of the\n,3-3-15 formula. This fertilizer on Eastern Shore\nsoils has produced a larger yield and perhaps a more\ndesirable potato than any other fertilizer formula that\nhas been tested. It should be applied at the rate ol\n500 to 750 pounds per acre, depending on the fer\ntility of the soil. The Experiment Station recom\nmends 750 pounds of this mixture*to the acre.\nThe 3-3-15 formula is very highly recommended,\nbut it has the objection that lower grade or inert\ningredients are commonly used in its preparation, and\nfreight costs are greater on an acre basis as a larger\nquantity per acre need be used. This fertilizer has\ngiven good results, but for the reasons given above\nthe 4-4-20 formula should have the preference. This\nformula, according to Experiment Station records,\nmay be applied from 750 to 1000 pounds per acre\naccording to the richness of the soil. The. Truck\nExperiment Station generally recommends the use\nof 1000 pounds of this mixture per acre.\nThe 3-6-12 formula has also given results at the\nExperiment Station, but no better than the 3-3-15\nor the 4-4-20. It should be used according to Experi\nment Station results at the same rate as the 3-3-15\nformula.\nThe 2-8-10 is perhaps the best of the old-time\nformulas for sweet potatoes. Experiments indicate\nthat it contains more phosphoric acid than is neces\n7\n4 sary, and is considerably deficient in potash. It is\ngenerally used at the rate of 800 to 1200 pounds per\nacre. We would not condemn the use of this fer\ntilizer but believe the first two mentioned are superior.\nLast year, a number of people used the 3-6-8, or 3-6-6\nformula. This was a special mixture which contained\nthe low nitrogen content that seems to be desirable,\nand a relatively high potash and relatively low phos\nphate content. Unquestionably, it is a good fertilizer.\nWhile leading in the right direction, it apparently\ndoes not have as much merit as the first two mention\ned, and we believe their use would be preferable.\nWe have called attention here to the use of these\nv new fertilizer formulas, since there is reason to believe\nthat their use would be beneficial not only from the\nstandpoint of yield per acre, but, also, from the\nquality ef potato that is grown. We would not make\nthese suggestions were it not that conclusive tests\nhave been made on the Eastern Shore for this long\nperiod of years and the results are approved by\nfertilizer experts and fertilizer companies. We trust\nthat all sweet potato fanners will give this .matter\ntheir consideration, and if this is done we feel sure\nthat they will not hesitate to use the new type form\nulas in preference to others.\nAPPLY SWEET POTATO FERTILIZERS PROP\nERLY: Sweet potato sprouts are easily injured by\nfertilizers. The use of fertilizer under sweet potato\nsprouts, or mixed with the soil when the sprouts are\nplanted, is unquestionably very dangerous and has\nresulted in much injury and poor stands. We have\nbelieved this for a number of years, have made some\ninvestigations, have talked to a good many farmers\nand have secured experimental data from the Truck\nExperiment Station. The results of these studies\nprove that the fertilizer should be applied as a side\ndressing after the sweet potato plants are well es\ntablished. Such applications show a markedly bet\nter stand, and they also prove conclusively that the\nmaturity of the sweet potato is not delayed by with\nholding the fertilizer until the vines are well es\ntablished. If anything, the growth of salable pota\ntoes is hastened due to the fact that the plants are\nnot injured. Beyond question, it is highly profitable\nfor the sweet potato farmer to plant his sweet\npotatoes and wait a week to ten days before he applies\nthe fertilizer as a side dressing.\nAn interesting, matter has come to our attention\nin regard to the method of planting sweet potato\nsprouts. A number of our farmers who have given\nthis matter very careful study have reached the con\nclusion that the row should be mounded a bit before\nsetting the plants, and that the slips should not bd\nplanted more than 2*4 ins. deep. Their conclusion,\ndetermined from their owm experiment, led them to\nbelieve that in this way they get earlier and better\nshaped potatoes.\nWhite Potato Prices\nOld Potatoes:\nPresque Isle, Maine, f. o. b. prices recently have\nranged from $2.85 to $3.10 per 150-pound sack, with\ndemand slow and market dull.\nIdaho 100-pound sacks f. o. b. prices mostly\n$2.25, with firm demand.\nNew Potatoes:\nNew York market Tuesday, March 4th: \u201cFlorida\ndouble headed barrels poor condition, $6.00 per barrel.\nDeducting freight and commission the f. o. b. price\nwould approximate $3.90 per barrel.\nThe price of both old and new stock is very dis\ncouraging. Unless the market strengthens the price\noutlook for the heavy flow of new stock next June\nand July is not good. Certainly, present prices and\nbusiness outlook do not encourage expansion of new\nplantings.\nEASTERN SNORE OF VIRGINIA PRODOCE EXCHANGE","height":"26848","width":"20284"}}
